  "prompt": "Does P = NP?",
  "response": "The question of whether \\( P \\) equals \\( NP \\) is one of the most famous unsolved problems in computer science and mathematics. As of October 2023, there is no known proof either proving or disproving that \\( P = NP \\).\n\nThe problem was formally introduced by Stephen Cook in 1971 in his seminal paper \"The Complexity of Theorem-Proving Procedures.\" It asks whether every problem for which a solution can be verified quickly (in polynomial time, \\( NP \\)) can also be solved quickly (again, in polynomial time, \\( P \\)).\n\nThe Clay Mathematics Institute has designated the \\( P \\) vs. \\( NP \\) problem as one of its seven \"Millennium Prize Problems,\" offering a million-dollar prize for a correct proof either way.\n\nIn summary, the status of \\( P \\) vs. \\( NP \\) remains an open question in theoretical computer science.",
